‚òï Hi friends! Today's mantra reminded me of Viktor Frankl's philosophy: that one of the few things we have full control over is our attitude and response towards any situation. I can't remember how many times I've been irritated or annoyed or felt some way towards something totally out of my control. But as the monk Thich Nhat Hanh reminds us, every moment is an opportunity to practice mindfulness. We can always change the story we are telling ourselves about situations or our own choices. I tell myself this, but also try to work on it by trying to catch myself and not dwelling long an emotion. Or if I can, I remove myself from it entirely. But often, when I'm faced with difficulty, I see it as test of my true inner strength and how independent of a person I truly am...and I need plenty work.

This practice was by far the hardest to do. Today marks 21 years since I survived an accident that almost took my life in high school. I never really think about it, and honestly,  I was going along oblivious about the whole thing for most of the day. Then, bam! It hit me in the middle of signing the date in one of my kid's exercise books. Since then, since I remembered, I'd been holding this lump in my chest. You know, the kind that's just balled up emotion. It wasn't budging, wouldn't move, that is, until I sat on the mat and started my practice. I think I cried until you got to the 7 min mark, then I took a deep breath and started again. It took me two tries to do this class today, but I was determined that I would do this practice, I was going to finish. And I did.
